data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**Key paradigm shift:** `Thread.Abort()` forcibly injects a `ThreadAbortException` (preemptive). In .NET 6+, it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. You must switch to **cooperative cancellation** where the work voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`.

### Inventory of APIs to replace

| Line | API | Status in .NET 8 |
|------|-----|-------------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` / `SYSLIB0006` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> for cancellation
    /// to respond promptly — cooperative cancellation cannot interrupt code that ignores the token.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Overload for callers that also hold their own cancellation token
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout,
                                    CancellationToken externalToken)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken was cancelled, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ComputeExpensiveResult(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — the work lambda now receives a CancellationToken
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => ComputeExpensiveResult(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### The work itself must cooperate

This is the **most critical pitfall**. The old `Thread.Abort` forcibly killed the thread regardless of what it was doing. Cooperative cancellation only works if the work checks the token:

```csharp
// BEFORE — didn't need to care about cancellation; Thread.Abort handled it
public DataSet ComputeExpensiveResult()
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        ProcessItem(item);  // Thread.Abort could kill mid-iteration
    }
    return BuildResult();
}

// AFTER — must check the token at regular checkpoints
public DataSet ComputeExpensiveResult(CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // cooperative checkpoint
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}
```

### Pitfalls specific to this migration

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|----------------|
| **Passing the token but never checking it** | Work runs to completion regardless of timeout. The `Task.Run` call only checks the token *before* starting; once running, it's up to your code. |
| **Blocking calls that ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep(60000)` won't be interrupted. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(60000)` or `await Task.Delay(60000, token)`. Same for synchronous socket/DB calls — use async overloads that accept a token. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using var cts = ...`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. Without it you'd swallow unrelated cancellations. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you call a library that doesn't accept a `CancellationToken` and blocks indefinitely, cooperative cancellation **cannot** stop it. Move that work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort. |

### If you cannot modify the work (escape hatch)

For truly uncooperative code that you can't add a token to, the **only** safe .NET 8 alternative is process isolation:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution with kill
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
